He inherited considerable property, which, when he went to Rome, and was received into the fashionable fast set, he proceeded to squander. In the year 62 Metellus Celer as praetor had his residence in Verona, and was accompanied by his wife Clodia, a woman of thirty-two, brilliant and profligate, ‘herself a poet and acquainted with Greek letters. This affair lasted some four yearS, until at least 57, when the final rupture with his “Lesbia '' occurred, and he went with Memmius to Bithy- nia, where he hoped to repair his shattered fortunes. During his absence his beloved brother Hortalus died, and he recorded his grief in a beautiful elegy. During the last three years of his short life he lived mostly at his country homes either at Sirmio, a promontory extending into what is now known as the Lago di Garda, or at Tibur, not far from Rome. Nothing is known of the exact date of his death3 some authorities give 54, others 47. His poems were lost until the fourteenth century, when two manuscripts were discovered in Verona. They consist of one hundredand sixteen pieces, many of them brief, others extending to a length of four hundred lines.
